"42% of the species of trees consisting of Europe's trees are at risk", warns the International Union for Nature Conservation (IUCN) in its "Red Paper of European Trees" published on Friday.
The list is headed by chestnuts and berry.
IUCN, an organisation based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It has been drawn up by experts who have come to the conclusion that 42% of the 454 species of trees found in Europe (and elsewhere in the world) are "highly endangered".
Among the causes of the Red Paper is the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
But the most at risk are these trees and bushes, which occur only or mainly on our continent.
As far as typically European wood stand is concerned, 58% of species are at risk from IUCN experts and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and bushes, are at risk of extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Paper mentions errors in the exploitation of wood-castan, accelerated urbanisation, too intensive logging of trees, and subsequently forest fires and changes in Europe's ecosystem.
According to the authors of the report, there is also a strong threat to the existence of many European varieties of bushes, mosses and vegetation.
"The follow-up of human activity leads to a gradual loss of European plant species and poses a danger in Europe of extinction of important and undervalued varieties that underpin European ecosystems and affect the health of our planet," said Luc Bas, who runs the IUCN European office.
